acies of the broadcasts.  aDifficult as it is to imagine today, in 1937 America's two leading media companies fought over which had the better claim to Shakespeare. The Battle of the Bard explores this episode in US cultural history when NBC and CBS competed to perform Shakespeare for an American audience in a low-risk setting that they hoped would bring prestige to their networks. The resulting fourteen broadcasts are among the more remarkable recreations of Shakespeare of their time. This lively and engaging book shows the cultural dominance of radio at the time, and tells the story of why the networks each wanted to lord Shakespeare's prestige over the other, how they put their series together, the critical reception, and the cultural impact and legacies of the broadcasts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aAdaptation.  aCBS.  aColumbia Shakespeare Cycle.  aEdward G. Robinson.  aHumphrey Bogart.  aJohn Barrymore.  aNBC.  aOld Time Radio.  aOrson Welles.  aRadio Shakespeare.  aRadio Summer Series.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311066152140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781641890786zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781641890786423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781641890786/original  a978-3-11-066152-1  Amsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK